,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENormal arterial blood flow is \u003Cstrong\u003Epulsatile and laminar with highest velocity centrally\u003C/strong\u003E. The pulsatile nature results from cardiac contractions, while laminar flow means blood moves in concentric layers with fastest flow in the centre and slowest flow near the vessel walls due to friction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuous and laminar with highest velocity peripherally\u003C/strong\u003E - Arterial flow is pulsatile, not continuous, and velocity is lowest at the periphery due to friction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulsatile and turbulent with uniform velocity\u003C/strong\u003E - While arterial flow is pulsatile, it is normally laminar, not turbulent. Velocity varies across the vessel diameter\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuous and turbulent with highest velocity centrally\u003C/strong\u003E - Arterial flow is pulsatile, not continuous, and is normally laminar rather than turbulent\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulsatile and laminar with uniform velocity\u003C/strong\u003E - While arterial flow is pulsatile and laminar, velocity is not uniform across the vessel diameter\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis pattern of flow can become disturbed in disease states such as atherosclerosis or at vessel bifurcations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Blood flow in arteries is pulsatile with highest velocity during systole and lowest during diastole.","Arterial flow is laminar under normal conditions, with fastest flow in the centre and slowest at the vessel walls.","Mean arterial flow velocity decreases as total cross-sectional area increases further from the heart."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of 